description:
&lt;p&gt;An exciting opportunity has arisen for an Infection Prevention and Control (IPC) Practitioner to support the delivery of the DHU IPC strategy across the Derbyshire, Leicestershire and Northants Divisions. The post holder will work in partnership with the Director of Nursing and Quality, Lead IPC Nurse and other members of the IPC Team and contribute to maintaining services of excellent quality that are safe and effective. This post line manages the IPC Health Care Assistants based across the Divisions. The role consists of a range of tasks, which require the exercise of initiative, autonomous working and decision making, requiring sound clinical knowledge and judgement.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The post holder will predominantly work autonomously with support and supervision from the IPC Lead. They will be responsible for ensuring that local IPC assurance processes including audits are undertaken and act as a professional point of contact for internal personnel and external key partners.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A commitment to the delivery of a safe and high quality service, excellence in clinical practice and continuous professional development are integral to the role and to the development and implementation of the IPC strategy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This post is subject to the Rehabilitation of Offenders Act (Exceptions Order) 1975 and as such it will be necessary for a submission for Disclosure to be made to the Criminal Records Bureau to check for any previous criminal convictions.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;DHU Healthcare is committed to Equality of Opportunity and welcomes application from all sections of the community.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For further details / informal visits contact:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Jenny Tilson, Director of Nursing &amp; Quality, Jenny.Tilson@DHUhealthcare.nhs.uk or Kimberley Davis IPC Practitioner Kimberley.Davis@DHUhealthcare.nhs.uk&lt;/p&gt;
